title: Meta-Principle
summary: The foundational axiom: nothing cannot recognize itself, forcing existence of non-trivial recognition.

title: The Ledger
summary: The universe's double-entry accounting system tracking all recognition events.

title: Recognition Events
summary: Atomic acts of distinction that write to the universal ledger with positive cost.

title: Dual-Balance
summary: Every recognition posts both debit and credit, ensuring global ledger closure.

title: Positive Cost
summary: All recognition events carry unavoidable positive cost, giving time its arrow.

title: Cost Functional J(x)
summary: The unique cost functional J(x)=½(x+1/x) that makes balance cheap and extremes expensive.

title: Recognition Length
summary: The fundamental length scale λ_rec = √(ℏG/c³) arising from recognition granularity.

title: Recognition Time
summary: The fundamental time quantum τ_0 = λ_rec/c for one recognition tick.

title: Coherence Energy
summary: The fundamental energy quantum E_coh from minimal recognition cost.

title: 8-Beat Cycle
summary: The fundamental eight-tick recognition cycle from traversing 3D voxel vertices.

title: Voxel Grid
summary: The discrete 3D lattice structure underlying spacetime geometry.

title: Causal Stride
summary: The maximum rate c = 1 voxel/tick at which recognition propagates.

title: φ-Scaling
summary: Self-similar scaling by the golden ratio φ in recognition hierarchies.

title: Ledger Curvature
summary: How recognition density curves the ledger geometry, manifesting as gravity.

title: LNAL Machine Code
summary: Light-Native Assembly Language: the universe's computational instruction set.

title: Recognition Paths
summary: All possible routes through recognition space, summed in quantum amplitudes.

title: Ledger Closure
summary: Mathematical requirement that all ledger entries sum to zero globally.

title: Recognition Density
summary: Local concentration of recognition events, related to energy-momentum.

title: Tick Synchronization
summary: Universe-wide coordination of recognition ticks enabling causality.

title: Recognition Interference
summary: How overlapping recognition paths create quantum interference patterns.

title: Ledger Topology
summary: The mathematical structure of recognition space and its transformations.

title: Recognition Algebra
summary: The mathematical operations governing recognition event composition.

title: Meta-Recognition
summary: Recognition events that recognize other recognition events.

title: Recognition Hierarchies
summary: Nested levels of recognition from quantum to cosmic scales.

title: Ledger Dynamics
summary: How the ledger state evolves through recognition event sequences.

title: Recognition Operators
summary: Mathematical operators that act on recognition states.

title: Ledger Invariants
summary: Quantities that remain constant under recognition transformations.

title: Recognition Symmetries
summary: Fundamental symmetries of the recognition process.

title: Causal Structure
summary: The partial ordering of recognition events in spacetime.

title: Recognition Entropy
summary: Information-theoretic measure of recognition state uncertainty.

title: Ledger Metrics
summary: Distance measures in recognition space and ledger geometry.

title: Recognition Fields
summary: Continuous field approximations to discrete recognition processes.

title: Quantum Recognition
summary: How quantum mechanics emerges from recognition statistics.

title: Recognition Thermodynamics
summary: Statistical mechanics of recognition event ensembles.

title: Ledger Gauge Theory
summary: Gauge theories arising from ledger symmetries and conservation laws.

title: Speed of Light
summary: The fixed stride c = 1 voxel/tick defining the universal speed limit.

title: Planck Constant
summary: The quantum of action ℏ relating energy and frequency in recognition events.

title: Golden Ratio φ
summary: The fundamental scaling ratio φ = (1+√5)/2 in recognition hierarchies.

title: Fine Structure Constant
summary: The dimensionless coupling α ≈ 1/137 governing electromagnetic interactions.

title: Gravitational Constant
summary: Newton's constant G relating mass-energy to spacetime curvature.

title: Dark Matter Fraction
summary: The cosmic dark matter fraction Ω_dm ≈ 0.2649 from voxel interference.

title: Cosmological Constant
summary: The cosmological constant Λ driving accelerated cosmic expansion.

title: Hubble Constant
summary: The current expansion rate H_0 ≈ 70 km/s/Mpc of the universe.

title: Boltzmann Constant
summary: The constant k_B relating temperature to average kinetic energy.

title: Avogadro Number
summary: The number N_A of particles in one mole of substance.

title: Elementary Charge
summary: The fundamental unit of electric charge e ≈ 1.602×10⁻¹⁹ C.

title: Electron Mass
summary: The rest mass of the electron m_e ≈ 9.109×10⁻³¹ kg.

title: Proton Mass
summary: The rest mass of the proton m_p ≈ 1.673×10⁻²⁷ kg.

title: Neutron Mass
summary: The rest mass of the neutron m_n ≈ 1.675×10⁻²⁷ kg.

title: Vacuum Permeability
summary: The magnetic permeability of free space μ_0 = 4π×10⁻⁷ H/m.

title: Vacuum Permittivity
summary: The electric permittivity of free space ε_0 ≈ 8.854×10⁻¹² F/m.

title: Gas Constant
summary: The universal gas constant R = N_A k_B ≈ 8.314 J/(mol·K).

title: Stefan-Boltzmann Constant
summary: The constant σ relating temperature to blackbody radiated power.

title: Wien Displacement Constant
summary: The constant b in Wien's displacement law for blackbody peak wavelength.

title: Rydberg Constant
summary: The constant R_∞ governing hydrogen spectral line frequencies.

title: Photon
summary: Massless particle carrying electromagnetic radiation and recognition signals.

title: Electron
summary: Fundamental charged lepton with spin-½ and negative electric charge.

title: Proton
summary: Positively charged baryon composed of two up quarks and one down quark.

title: Neutron
summary: Neutral baryon composed of one up quark and two down quarks.

title: Neutrino
summary: Nearly massless neutral lepton interacting only via weak nuclear force.

title: Muon
summary: Heavy unstable lepton, essentially a heavy electron with 200× mass.

title: Tau
summary: Heaviest charged lepton, unstable with very short lifetime.

title: Up Quark
summary: Lightest quark with +2/3 electric charge, component of protons.

title: Down Quark
summary: Second-lightest quark with -1/3 electric charge, component of neutrons.

title: Strange Quark
summary: Third-generation quark with -1/3 charge and strangeness quantum number.

title: Charm Quark
summary: Fourth-generation quark with +2/3 charge and charm quantum number.

title: Bottom Quark
summary: Fifth-generation quark with -1/3 charge and bottom quantum number.

title: Top Quark
summary: Heaviest known quark with +2/3 charge and enormous mass.

title: W Boson
summary: Massive gauge boson mediating weak nuclear interactions.

title: Z Boson
summary: Neutral massive gauge boson mediating weak nuclear interactions.

title: Gluon
summary: Massless gauge boson mediating strong nuclear force between quarks.

title: Higgs Boson
summary: Scalar boson responsible for giving mass to other particles.

title: Quantum State
summary: Mathematical description of a quantum system's complete information.

title: Wave Function
summary: Complex-valued function encoding quantum state probability amplitudes.

title: Superposition
summary: Quantum principle allowing states to exist in multiple configurations simultaneously.

title: Spacetime
summary: The unified 4D fabric of space and time in Einstein's relativity.

title: Gravity
summary: Curvature of spacetime caused by mass-energy, manifesting as attractive force.

title: General Relativity
summary: Einstein's theory describing gravity as spacetime curvature.

title: Special Relativity
summary: Einstein's theory of space and time without gravity.

title: Black Holes
summary: Regions where spacetime curvature becomes so extreme that nothing escapes.

title: Event Horizon
summary: The boundary around a black hole beyond which nothing can escape.

title: Hawking Radiation
summary: Thermal radiation emitted by black holes due to quantum effects.

title: Geodesics
summary: Shortest paths through curved spacetime, followed by freely falling objects.

title: Tidal Forces
summary: Differential gravitational forces causing stretching and compression.

title: Gravitational Waves
summary: Ripples in spacetime fabric propagating at the speed of light.

title: Big Bang
summary: The initial expansion of the universe from a hot, dense state.

title: Cosmic Microwave Background
summary: Relic radiation from the early universe when atoms first formed.

title: Dark Matter
summary: Invisible matter comprising ~27% of the universe, detected via gravity.

title: Dark Energy
summary: Mysterious energy causing the universe's accelerating expansion.

title: Inflation
summary: Rapid exponential expansion in the universe's first moments.

title: Hubble's Law
summary: The relationship between galaxy distance and recession velocity.

title: Redshift
summary: The stretching of light wavelengths due to cosmic expansion.

title: Galaxy Formation
summary: How galaxies formed and evolved from primordial density fluctuations.

title: Star Formation
summary: The process by which gas clouds collapse to form new stars.

title: Stellar Evolution
summary: The complete lifecycle of stars from birth to death.
